------------------------------------------------------------------

What I did:

Installed VirtualBox on Linux Mint

Created two VMs:

web-vm â†’ Web Server

db-vm â†’ Database Server

Installed Ubuntu Server on both VMs

Configured network adapters:

Adapter 1 â†’ NAT (internet)

Adapter 2 â†’ Host-only (vboxnet0) for private subnet

Brought up host-only interfaces and assigned IPs:

web-vm â†’ 192.168.56.101

db-vm â†’ 192.168.56.102

Installed SSH server on db-vm

Verified ping connectivity between web-vm â†” db-vm

Installed MySQL server on db-vm

Installed MySQL client on web-vm

Created MySQL user webuser bound to web-vm IP

Created MySQL database webdb

Verified SSH and MySQL connectivity from web-vm to db-vm

What problems I faced:

VirtualBox AMD-V error:

Could not enable AMD-V (KVM conflict)

Second network adapter (enp0s8) not appearing

Could not assign host-only IP

SSH from web-vm to db-vm not working initially

MySQL remote connection errors

111 Connection refused

1045 Authentication error

1049 Unknown database

No MySQL client installed on web-vm

What I did to fix that problem:

AMD-V / KVM conflict

Created /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-kvm.conf with:

	blacklist kvm_amd
	blacklist kvm


Ran sudo update-initramfs -u and rebooted

Second network adapter not detected

Ensured Adapter 2 was enabled in VirtualBox settings

Brought up interface:

	sudo ip link set enp0s8 up
	sudo dhclient enp0s8


SSH issues

Installed SSH server on db-vm:

	sudo apt install openssh-server -y
	sudo systemctl enable ssh
	sudo systemctl start ssh


SSH from web-vm then worked:

	ssh ubuntu@192.168.56.102


MySQL connection errors

Verified MySQL was listening on all interfaces (0.0.0.0:3306)

Installed MySQL client on web-vm:

	sudo apt install mysql-client -y


Ensured webuser@192.168.56.101 existed and used mysql_native_password plugin

Created database webdb and granted privileges:

	CREATE DATABASE webdb;
	GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON webdb.* TO 'webuser'@'192.168.56.101';
	FLUSH PRIVILEGES;


Unknown database error

Connected without specifying a database first

Created webdb as the proper database for web-vm

Overall achievement:

Successfully set up a two-tier VM environment simulating a cloud architecture:

Web tier (web-vm)

Database tier (db-vm)

Established private network (host-only) for inter-VM communication

Verified SSH and MySQL connectivity

Practiced real-world troubleshooting skills: KVM conflicts, network setup, MySQL auth, client installation

Built a mini cloud lab environment suitable for future exercises like connecting Nginx â†’ MySQL or simulating AWS EC2 + RDS




